# hpc-job-analyst — System and Workflow Context
#
# This file teaches the AI analysis tool about your HPC system and the
# scientific workflows your users run.  It is loaded automatically at
# runtime if placed in one of these locations (all that exist are merged):
#
#   <install_prefix>/etc/hpc-job-analyst/system-context.md  — installer/operator
#   /etc/hpc-job-analyst/system-context.md                  — system-wide admin
#   ~/.config/hpc-job-analyst/system-context.md             — per-user
#
# Write this file in plain Markdown.  Use level-2 (##) headers to separate
# sections.  Recommended sections are shown below with placeholder text.
# Delete sections that are not relevant to your site.
#
# IMPORTANT: Only describe workflows your users actually run on this system.
# The AI applies each workflow section only when it detects that workflow in
# the job log.  It will not cross-apply guidance from one workflow to another.

---

## System: <Your System Name>

<!--
Describe the HPC system: hardware generation, interconnect type and fabric
library (e.g., InfiniBand/UCX, Slingshot/OFI), filesystems, Slurm partition
names, and any common failure signatures visible in job logs.

Example:
-->

<Your System Name> is a <hardware description> cluster running <OS> with
Slurm as its workload manager.  Compute partitions include:

- **<partition1>** — <description>
- **<partition2>** — <description>

The parallel filesystem is <filesystem type> mounted under <path>.
The MPI library is <MPI library>, and the high-speed interconnect is
<interconnect> using the <fabric interface> interface.

Common transient infrastructure failure signatures in job logs include:
- "<example error string 1>"
- "<example error string 2>"

When these appear, the failure is an infrastructure failure.  The primary
recommendation is to resubmit the job.

---

## Workflow: <Workflow Name>

<!--
Add one section per workflow your users run.  For each workflow, describe:

1. What the workflow manages automatically (so the AI does not suggest steps
   the workflow already handles, such as restart file management).
2. What the correct user recovery steps are for a transient failure.
3. Any workflow-specific terminology that appears in job logs.

Example for a segmented climate model workflow:
-->

<Workflow Name> is recognized in job logs by the presence of <identifier>.

### What the workflow manages automatically

- <Feature 1 the workflow handles internally — do not suggest manual steps for this>
- <Feature 2>

### Recovery for transient infrastructure failures

For a transient failure (network, node, or filesystem error), the correct
recovery is:

1. <Step 1>
2. <Step 2>

Users should NOT manually <action the workflow handles>, as <workflow name>
manages this automatically.

### Recovery for model/software failures

If the log contains <model error indicators>, the failure is a model error.
Users should <action>, or contact <support team>.

---

## General guidance

<!--
Site-wide rules that apply regardless of workflow.  Examples:
- Quota check commands
- Node exclusion policy
- Any site-specific Slurm flags users should or should not use
-->

- Never suggest that users drain nodes or change node state; those are
  administrator operations.
- For quota errors, users can check their usage with <quota command>.
